CSRF – Lab 2

Summary:

This lab contains a Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) vulnerability in the email change functionality. Although the application attempts to implement CSRF protection using a token, the validation is only applied to certain HTTP request methods.
Because of this misconfiguration, the CSRF protection can be bypassed by changing the request method.

Exploitation:

After intercepting the email change request using Burp Suite, it was observed that the request includes a csrf parameter. Modifying this token causes the request to be rejected, indicating that CSRF validation exists.
However, when the request method is changed from POST to GET, the server no longer validates the CSRF token. This allows the attacker to bypass the protection mechanism.

By crafting a malicious HTML page that sends a GET request to the vulnerable endpoint, a logged-in victim can be forced to change their email address.

CSRF PoC:

<form action="https://YOUR-LAB-ID.web-security-academy.net/my-account/change-email">
    <input type="hidden" name="email" value="attacker@web-security-academy.net">
</form>

<script>
document.forms[0].submit();
</script>


When the victim visits this page while authenticated, their browser automatically sends the request and updates their account email.

Impact:

Attackers can perform unauthorized actions on behalf of authenticated users despite the presence of an incomplete CSRF defense.

Mitigation:

* Validate CSRF tokens for all HTTP methods.
* Restrict sensitive actions to POST requests only.
* Implement SameSite cookies and Origin/Referer validation.
